post_text:
The Willow Springs R-IV Schools is announcing we will extend the annual summer food service program sponsored by the U.S. Department of Agriculture. Free meals are available to all children in the Willow Springs school district aged 18 and younger from September 14, 2020 through December 31, 2020. Breakfast and lunch will be served daily Monday through Friday for seated classes in each school.

Free lunches will also be provided by curbside pickup Monday through Friday at 11:15 am at the elementary school. The curbside pickup will be for children aged 18 and younger who reside in the Willow Springs school district but are currently not enrolled or are doing distance learning. If you would like to pick up meals, please call (417) 252-6103 and tell us how many meals you will be picking up each day. It is important that you call in and reserve meals so we know how many to prepare.

post_text: The Willow Springs School District places the health and safety of students and staff as its’ highest priority. In the event of a positive test for Covid-19, school district staff work directly with Howell County Health Department staff on contact tracing to provide information on students who have had close contact with the person testing positive. The health department follows the Centers for Disease Control guidelines. The school district will always follow the guidance of the health department regarding excluding students or staff from school for a period of time due to potential exposure. If a student is to be quarantined, the parents of the students will be contacted directly by the health department.

The Willow Springs School District has been made aware of the community-wide boil advisory now in effect. We are working on a plan to get through this short-term problem. For the safety of staff and students, all bottle filling stations will be turned off during this advisory. Parents are encouraged to send a pre-packaged bottle of water with your student to school tomorrow, if possible. Bottled water will also be provided to students and staff until such time that the boil advisory is cancelled. The school's food service department is taking the necessary precautions and following the guidelines of the boil advisory.

Thank you for your continued support.

post_text:
Greetings Willow Springs R-IV Parents and Students.

We certainly hope this letter finds each of you safe and healthy. At the July 30th special Board of Education meeting, the Willow Springs BOE approved the school district’s Reentry Plan for the 2020 fall semester. We are currently in the process of finalizing enrollment for the 2020-2021 school term. We expect to see all of our students back for the new school year. However, if you do not plan to have your student attend regular seated school, it is important that you contact your school’s office no later than Friday, August 14, 2020 to discuss alternative options to continue your child’s education. If you plan to have your child attend school in person, there is no action needed on your part. The first day of school is Monday, August 24, 2020.

For your convenience, the phone numbers of all three school offices are noted below:

Willow Springs Elementary School:
(417) 469-2474
Willow Springs Middle School:
(417) 469-3211
Willow Springs High School:
(417) 469-2114

Sincerely,
Willow Springs R-IV School Administration

Important Information Concerning PreK and Kindergarten Screening:
The following dates have been set for PreK and Kindergarten screening for Willow Springs’ students entering PreK and Kindergarten for the 2020-21 school year.
- PreK Screening: Monday, August 3, 2020
- Kindergarten Screening: August 4-5, 2020
*Parents can call the elementary school from 8:00 am to 3:00 pm during Summer School in July to schedule an appointment.
*Parents need to bring a birth certificate and shot records for their student(s).
*For families who are new to the district, a piece of mail with your physical address also needs to be provided.

Hey WSHS!
Hope all is well as we enter what would've been the seniors last week of school. Just a couple of updates for you today.

1. The last day to pick up your belongings from the high school will be Saturday, May 9 from 9:00-12:00. Most things are gone by now, but this is your last call.

2. Still having lots of questions on prom and graduation. Both events are still scheduled for June 13 and 14. All details will be determined at a later date. We will have more information for you by Memorial Day, but I'm sure you can understand, things change quickly with our current situation and we don't want to make a decision we have to go back on later.

3. It's Teacher Appreciation Day! Do me a BIG favor and email some words of encouragement to one of your teachers (past or present) today!

See you soon!

Mr. Spence

post_text:
Hey WSHS!

Hope you are all well! Please watch the video below for some visual updates and a very special birthday surprise at the end! Next week is pick up week in the district. On the assigned days from 8-3, you can pick up your belongings. Seniors, you can also pick up your graduation items, if they have been paid in full. If you still owe money to Jostens, you can pay online at thegraduationcenter.com or by calling 573-546-7366. Please bring back any books you have at home. Seniors, if you have a lunch credit on your account, the balance will be applied to a younger sibling or mailed back to your parents. Next week will also be the final update for At-Home Learning. Even though school is closed for the year, the Willow Springs school district will continue providing learning resources for students and distribution of meals to children 18 years of age and younger. The meals will continue to be distributed on Monday, Wednesday and Friday from 11:00 a.m. to 12:30 pm.

post_text:
The Willow Springs School District will be participating in the “Be The Light” campaign that has been moving throughout the United States. The idea is to turn on your stadium lights to show support for the senior class of 2020 and spring sport athletes, coaches, and families. The lights will be a symbol showing that we are thinking of them and are looking forward to returning to school and competition.

The lights will be turned on Friday, April 10 at 8:20 pm (20:20) for twenty minutes to honor this year’s senior class and spring sports participants.

People hoping to witness this event are encouraged to drive by Booster and Palenske Field and provide a honk or two. Participates are to remain in their vehicles in order to adhere to the social distancing guidelines.

post_text:
Middle school students can now use their school email account to directly communicate with their teachers! This account will only send or receive email to and from other accounts within our school system, and it is monitored by our firewall.
Student email addresses are the last two numbers of their graduation year followed by an underscore, then their last name followed by @willowbears.com. Their password is their Google password that they use at school.
Example for a 5th grader: 27_smith@willowbears.com.
If there are other students in the same grade with the same last name, they may need to follow their last name with the first initial of their first name (smithj).
All they have to do is go to Gmail and log in.
We hope this makes it easier to stay in touch with teachers until we are all together again!

post_text:
MSHSAA Email:
I am emailing you concerning rumors over spring sports. Our office and the MSHSAA Board have not had any discussions about canceling the spring season! Evidence of that is the fact that we released our class and district assignments this morning at 7:00 am. We are monitoring what is happening from the Missouri Department of Health, the Governor's Office, and the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education. The situation is very fluid, but if it is determined to suspend any contests and practices, we will notify our schools with instructions and look at any adjustments to the by-laws to allow the post-season to be played. Again, at this time, we have not altered the spring season, and encourage each school to make the best decision for their school and community on regular season. Please help spread this word and squash any rumors floating in your community.

post_text:
The Willow Springs Chess Club Championship took place Thursday night. Willow Elementary team won second place, represented by Adalynn Siler, who got second individual as well. Middle school team won second place. Josiah Wills and Isaac Miller tied for second individual, Vivienne Iacovleva, John Moore, and Daniel Iacovlev tied for 4th, Abbie Wills and David Dudko tied for 12th, Jeffrey Brasier and Vasiliy Zavalin had a win each. High school team won first place. Owen Moore and Patrick Burch tied for second, Drake Marshell was seventh, Sven Woodard and Colton Wood tied for 10th, Gabe Story had a win, and Isaac Mayberry and Nolan Smith had a tie each. Great job!

State Championship next week has been canceled, unfortunately. Have a good and healthy break!

post_text:
The Willow Springs R-IV School District is seeking a person of integrity, highly organized, with exceptional interpersonal skills for the position of secretary to the Special Education Department. Proficiency in the use of the Microsoft Office Suite and the student information database is necessary.

This is a ten month position with health and life insurance and sick leave. Salary is commensurate with experience.

This person will be the initial point of contact with all communication coming into the Special Education office. Duties will include maintenance of student records, maintaining special education records, managing Medicaid records and payments, and preparing special education reports and letters and other duties as assigned.

Experienced applicants need to apply at the Office of the Superintendent, 904 Old Springfield Road. Applications will be accepted through March 25th.

E.O.E.

post_text: This past Saturday, Willow chess team competed at the Glenwood tournament. High school team won the competition, with Owen Moore coming in second, Patrick Burch and Drake Marshell tying for 4th, Gabe Story tied for 9th, and Colton Wood had a win and a draw. Middle school team won second place, with Abigail Wills tying for first, Isaac Miller in 3rd, Daniel Iacovlev tying for 10th, and John Moore in 18th. Our Junior High team was 4th overall, with Josiah Wills getting 4th place, and Vivienne Iacovleva tying for 9th. Our elementary team only had one warrior this time. Otto Schuette came in 3rd, and alone got us a 4th team spot. Great work!

post_text: The Willow Springs R-IV School District is looking for that perfect person to join the Willow Springs Bear family. Applications are currently being accepted for the position of full-time custodian. We want interested applicants who take pride in their work, who are dependable and a good role model for children. Applicants must be able to pass a background check. Besides salary, benefits include district-paid life and health insurance, as well as sick leave and vacation leave. We will be accepting applications until Friday, February 21, 2020. Applications may be picked up at the Superintendent’s Office at 904 Old Springfield Road. Equal Opportunity Employer. Don’t miss out on this opportunity to join the Willow Springs R-IV School District Team!

post_text:
Congratulations to the Willow chess team on another great performance at Willow Open chess tourney!
In elementary, Adalynn Siler and Aubrey Miller brought home first place team trophy. Hannah Wills, a WS homeschooler, tied for first individual spot.
In Middle school division, Abigail Wills won first individual, Isaac Miller and John Moore tied for second, Daniel Iacovlev tied for 7th. Together, they won the first team honors.
In Junior High, Josiah Wills tied for first, Vivienne Iacovleva tied for 5th individual place, and together with Jeffrey Brasier, they were fourth team.
In High school, Owen Moore and Patrick Burch tied for 3rd, Rogan Traver and Drake Marshell tied for 6th, Martin Leija and Gabe Story tied for 13th, Colton Wood had 2.5 pts, and Jonathan Baker had a win. Together, they earned a first team spot and won the tournament, leaving West Plains in a distant second. Way to go!
Recent graduate Eli Moore also won a medal in the adult division.
Thank you for your hard work and thank you for showing up! Galena is next on Feb 8.
